Predicting Average Movie Rating

Caitlyn Vasquez

2024-03-23

Introduction

The purpose of this project is to develop a model that will predict the average rating (of TMDb users) on a movie.

Why?

As a movie enthusiast, I’ve enjoyed a lot of exceptional films, along with some lackluster ones. The idea of predicting the average vote of a film strikes me as a valuable tool to fine-tune my movie choices. By using machine learning to predict how audiences rate films collectively, I hope to discover more crowd-pleasing movies while avoiding the duds. I’m curious to explore the factors that influence these ratings without having to watch it myself.

There are multiple reasons why predicting overall rating for a movie can be useful:

Recommendation System

Accurate predictions of movie ratings enable the creation of recommendation systems. By understanding users’ preferences and behaviors, platforms like TMDb, streaming services, or movie rental services can recommend personalized movie suggestions to users. This enhances user experience and engagement by offering relevant content tailored to individual tastes.

Content Curation

Predicted ratings can assist content creators, producers, and distributors in understanding audience preferences. This allows them to create movies with similar content that aligns with audience expectations, leading to increased viewership and revenue.

Market Analysis

Analyzing predicted movie ratings can serve as a tool for evaluating the potential success of upcoming movies. It provides valuable insights into trends and audience preferences, guiding marketing strategies for optimized performance in the film industry.

Exploring and Tidying Raw Data

Variable Selection

To get a better understanding, let’s explore our data!

dim(movie)
## [1] 45466    24

The dataset comprises 45,466 rows and 24 columns, which means we have 45,466 unique movies and 24 variables. Among these variables, vote_average serves as our response variable, but that still leaves us with 23 predictor variables. Let’s refine our selection!

There are a few repetitive variables in the data (i.e. keep original_title and omit title, etc.) and some variables that are not as relevant when determining average vote/TMDb user ratings (i.e. homepage, poster_path, etc.). So we will omit these columns and keep the columns of relevant variables (as described under Codebook).

# Keeping selected variables
movie <- movie %>%
  select(c('budget', 'genres', 'id', 'original_title', 'popularity', 'production_companies', 'release_date', 'revenue', 'runtime', 'vote_average', 'vote_count'))

head(movie)

Tidying Variables

The genres variable appears as a list since some movies have more than one genre. For simplification purposes, we are going to create a new variable genre with the first listed genre from genres. The production_companies variable also appears as a list so we will do the same to that variable.

movie['genre'] = gsub("\\[\\{'id':\\s*\\d+,\\s*'name':\\s*'([^']*)'.*", "\\1", movie$genres)

movie['production_company'] = gsub("\\[\\{'name':\\s*'([^']*)'.*", "\\1", movie$production_companies)

movie <- movie %>%
  select(-c('genres', 'production_companies'))

For further simplification purposes when exploring the data, let’s create a new variable release_year and extract the year from the release_date variable accordingly.

movie['release_year'] <- substr(movie$release_date, 1, 4)

movie <- movie %>%
  select(-c('release_date'))

# Tidied data
head(movie)

Now, let’s check for any missing data.

sum(is.na(movie))

It appears that we have 281 missing data. Let’s omit those.

movie <- na.omit(movie)

Let’s double check to make sure they were successfully removed.

sum(is.na(movie))
## [1] 0

We no longer have any missing data, however, we have a good amount of data where the attributing values do not make sense. For instance, some of the values from genres and production_companies were empty strings to begin with (i.e. the corresponding value is ‘[]’).

One significant challenge posed by this dataset is the presence of zero values in certain variables where such values are logically implausible. The decision to eliminate these rows results in a reduction from approximately 45,000 observations to around 5,000, which unfortunately means we are omitting a lot of movies. Imputing the data for those zero values is not advisable, so we will remove those rows. Luckily, the remaining 5,000 observations still constitute a sizable dataset.

# Remove any movies and production companies with no data (i.e. the corresponding value is '[]') as well as any rows where the runtime, revenue, and budget is 0.

For further information about our variables, explore the Codebook below!

Codebook

  • budget (dbl): total budget of movie in USD
  • id (chr): unique identifier for each movie on TMDb
  • original_title (chr): title of movie in its original language
  • popularity (dbl): “lifetime” metric from TMDd to measure popularity of movie and is impacted by the following: number of votes for the day, number of views for the day, number of users who marked it as a “favorite” for the day, number of users who added it to their “watchlist” for the day, release date, number of total votes, previous days score
  • revenue (dbl): total revenue of movie in USD
  • runtime (dbl): duration of the movie in minutes
  • vote_average (dbl): average of all TMBd user ratings for a movie (0-10)
  • vote_count (dbl): number of voters of movie
  • genre (chr): primary genre of movie
  • production_company (chr): production company of movie
  • release_year (dbl): year of movie release

Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA)

Let’s explore our data!

Vote Average

First, we’ll take a look at the distribution of our response variable, vote_average.

ggplot(data=movie, aes(x=vote_average)) +
  geom_histogram(bins=100, fill="pink") +
  theme_bw() +
  ggtitle("Distribution of Movie Vote Average") +
  xlim(0,10) +
  labs (x="Vote Average", y="Count")

The distribution of vote_average is symmetric with a peak around 6.3. This means the most common average TMBd user rating from our dataset is approximately 6.3/10. From the plot, the ratings range from ~1.5 to ~9, which makes sense since ratings are on a 0-10 scale.

The data contains movies from a wide variety of genres. Let’s see how many movies are in each genre category.

movie %>%

  geom_bar(stat = "identity", fill = "pink") +

‘Drama’ appears to be the most frequent genre, with over 1250 movies in that category, followed by ‘Comedy,’ ‘Action,’ ‘Adventure,’ ‘Horror,’ and ‘Crime.’ The remaining 14 genres each have under 250 movies in their respective categories.

Since we have 20 genres, let’s narrow that down! We’ll leave the top five genres and lump the remaining genres into an ‘other_genres’ category.

movie <- movie %>%
  filter(!is.na(genre)) %>%
  mutate(genre = fct_lump(genre, n = 5, other_level = "other_genres"))

Production Company

Production company can play a significant role in determining the average rating of a movie. Certain companies may have a reputation of producing high-quality films or may have larger budgets to afford better resources. These attributes have the potential to influence the rating of a film. Let’s take a look at the most common production companies in our data set.

Looking at the bar plot of the top 7 most common production companies, we see that Paramount Pictures has produced the most number of movies (over 300), followed closely by Universal Pictures. If we add up the counts, these 7 production companies produce almost a third of the movies in the dataset.

We will simplify our production_company variable, so, we will use the top two production companies and lump the rest into an ‘other_companies’ category.

Model Preparation

Before we build and fit our models, we must prepare them first. We need to split the data, create the recipe, and create folds for k-fold cross validation.

Splitting the Data

First, let’s split the data into two sets: training and testing. The training set is a portion of the data set that is used to teach the model patterns and relationships, hence “training.” The testing set is a separate portion reserved for evaluating the model’s performance on unseen data. I have chosen to split my data so that 70% goes towards training and 30% goes towards testing.

set.seed(123)
movie_split <- initial_split(movie, strata = "vote_average", prop = 0.7)

movie_train <- training(movie_split)
movie_test <- testing(movie_split)

Let’s take a look at the dimensions of our dataset as well as the training and testing sets to ensure we have a 70/30 split.

dim(movie)
## [1] 5193   11
dim(movie_train)
## [1] 3633   11
dim(movie_test)
## [1] 1560   11

Great! Let’s move on to the next step of our model preparation.

Creating the Recipe

We will create a universal recipe for all of our models to use. This recipe will consist of the predictor variables we explored in the EDA step. The 8 predictors are: budget, popularity, revenue, runtime, vote_count, genre, production_company, and release_year.

Since genre and production_company are categorical variables, we’ll make them dummy variables.

Lastly, we’ll normalize our variables.

movie_recipe <- recipe(vote_average ~ budget + popularity + revenue + runtime + vote_count + genre + production_company + release_year, data = movie_train) %>%
  step_dummy(genre) %>%
  step_dummy(production_company) %>%
  step_nzv(all_predictors()) %>%
  step_normalize(all_predictors()) 

movie_recipe %>% prep() %>% bake(new_data=movie_train)

K-fold Cross Validation

We will create 5 folds for k-fold cross validation. This means that the dataset is divided into k subsets of approximately equal size (hence 5 folds). The model is trained k times, each time using k-1 folds for training and the remaining fold for validation. After each training-validation iteration, the performance of the model is evaluated using a metric, in this case RMSE, on the validation set. This results in k performance estimates. The k performance estimates are averaged to a single performance metric that represents the overall performance of the model.

By using k-fold cross validation, we can get a more reliable estimate of the model’s performance compared to a single train-test split. It helps mitigate the bias and variance that can arise from a single train-test split and provides a better assessment of how the model will perform on unseen data.

movie_folds <- vfold_cv(movie_train, v = 5, strata = "vote_average")

Building and Fitting/Tuning the Models

Let’s move on to constructing our models! We will be building five models: linear regression, k-nearest neighbors, elastic net, pruned decision trees, and random forest. I have chosen Root Mean Squared Error (RMSE) to evaluate the performance of these models. RMSE measures the average difference between a model’s predicted values and the actual values. So, a smaller RMSE means less average difference between the predicted and actual values which is better.

There are multiple steps we must take to fit these models, so let’s get started!

Model Setup

For each model we’ll specify the model we want to fit, the parameters we want to tune, the engine the model comes from, and the mode, which in this case is regression.

# Linear Regression
lm_model <- linear_reg() %>%
  set_engine("lm")

# K-Nearest Neighbors
knn_model <- nearest_neighbor(neighbors = tune()) %>%
  set_engine("kknn") %>%
  set_mode("regression")

# Elastic Net
en_model <- linear_reg(mixture = tune(),
                       penalty = tune()) %>%
  set_engine("glmnet") %>%
  set_mode("regression")

# Pruned Decision Trees
pd_model <- decision_tree(cost_complexity = tune()) %>%
  set_engine("rpart") %>%
  set_mode("regression")

# Random Forest
rf_model <- rand_forest(mtry = tune(),
                        trees = tune(),
                        min_n = tune()) %>%
  set_engine("ranger", importance = "impurity") %>%
  set_mode("regression")

Workflow

Next, we’ll set up the workflows for each model by adding the respective model and the recipe.

# Linear Regression
lm_workflow <- workflow() %>%
  add_model(lm_model) %>%
  add_recipe(movie_recipe)

# K-Nearest Neighbors
knn_workflow <- workflow() %>%
  add_model(knn_model) %>%
  add_recipe(movie_recipe)

# Elastic Net
en_workflow <- workflow() %>%
  add_model(en_model) %>%
  add_recipe(movie_recipe)

# Pruned Decision Trees
pd_workflow <- workflow() %>%
  add_model(pd_model) %>%
  add_recipe(movie_recipe)

# Random Forest
rf_workflow <- workflow() %>%
  add_model(rf_model) %>%
  add_recipe(movie_recipe)

Creating Grids

Then, we’ll create tuning grids to specify the ranges for the tuning parameters and the number of levels.

# Linear Regression
# No grid because no tuning parameters

# K-Nearest Neighbors
knn_grid <- grid_regular(neighbors(range = c(1, 30)), levels = 5)

# Elastic Net
en_grid <- grid_regular(penalty(),
                        mixture(range = c(0,1)),
                        levels = 10)

# Pruned Decision Trees
pd_grid <- grid_regular(cost_complexity(range = c(-3, -1)), levels = 10)

# Random Forest
rf_grid <- grid_regular(mtry(range = c(1, 6)), 
                        trees(range = c(100, 1000)),
                        min_n(range = c(5, 20)),
                        levels = 8)

Tuning

Now, we’ll tune the models by specifying the workflow, the k-fold cross validation, and the tuning grid.

# Linear Regression
# No tuning

# K-Nearest Neighbors
knn_tune <- tune_grid(
  object = knn_workflow, 
  resamples = movie_folds, 
  grid = knn_grid
)

# Elastic Net
en_tune <- tune_grid(
  object = en_workflow,
  resamples = movie_folds,
  grid = en_grid
)

# Pruned Decision Trees
pd_tune <- tune_grid(
  object = pd_workflow,
  resamples = movie_folds,
  grid = pd_grid
)

# Random Forest
rf_tune <- tune_grid(
  object = rf_workflow,
  resamples = movie_folds,
  grid = rf_grid
)

Save Tuned Models

Let’s save the tuned models to an RDA file to avoid rerunning the model…

# Linear Regression
# No tuning

# K-Nearest Neighbors
save(knn_tune, file = "~/pstat 131/FINAL PROJECT/knn_tune.rda")

# Elastic Net
save(en_tune, file = "~/pstat 131/FINAL PROJECT/en_tune.rda")

# Pruned Decision Trees 
save(pd_tune, file = "~/pstat 131/FINAL PROJECT/pd_tune.rda")

# Random Forest
save(rf_tune, file = "~/pstat 131/FINAL PROJECT/rf_tune.rda")

Collect Metrics

Finally, we’ll collect the metrics and extract the lowest RMSE value from each model.

# Linear Regression
lm_fit <- fit_resamples(lm_workflow, resamples = movie_folds)
lm_rmse <- collect_metrics(lm_fit) %>%
  dplyr::slice(1)
lm_rmse
# K-Nearest Neighbors
knn_rmse <- show_best(knn_tune, metric = "rmse", n = 1)
knn_rmse
# Elastic Net
en_rmse <- show_best(en_tune, metric = "rmse", n = 1) 
en_rmse
# Pruned Decision Trees 
pd_rmse <- show_best(pd_tune, metric = "rmse", n = 1)
pd_rmse
# Random Forest
rf_rmse <- show_best(rf_tune, metric = "rmse", n = 1)
rf_rmse

Regarding models with tuning parameters, we see that k-nearest neighbors performed best with neighbors = 22 and random forest with mtry = 6, trees = 485, and min_n = 13. Unfortunately, some complications arose with elastic net and pruned decision trees. From the elastic net tibble, it performed best when penalty = 1e-10 and mixture = 0.66667, but it only tested on one fold resulting in std_err = NA. Pruned decision trees performed best with cost_complexity = 0.00278 but only tested on four folds.

Despite encountering some drawbacks, we were able to obtain RMSE values from each model!

Model Results

Let’s take a look at our model results and compare them!

# Create tibble of all models and corresponding RMSE
rmse_tibble <- tibble(Model = c("Linear Regression", "K-Nearest Neighbors", "Elastic Net", "Pruned Decision Trees", "Random Forest"), RMSE = c(lm_rmse$mean, knn_rmse$mean, en_rmse$mean, pd_rmse$mean, rf_rmse$mean))

# Arrange by lowest RMSE (best)
rmse_tibble <- rmse_tibble %>%
  arrange(RMSE)

rmse_tibble

Overall, the random forest model (Model 216) produced the lowest RMSE and thus performed the best! Following the random forest model were: k-nearest neighbors, linear regression, pruned decision trees and, lastly, elastic net.

Model Autoplots

Elastic Net Plot

autoplot(en_tune, metric = "rmse")

In the elastic net plot, the amount of regularization, on the x-axis, is the penalty hyperparameter and the values of mixture are represented by the different colored lines. We notice that penalty < 1e-02 results in the lowest RMSE and that mixture does not have a significant effect.

Pruned Decision Trees

autoplot(pd_tune, metric = "rmse")

From the pruned decision trees plot, the range that produces the lowest RMSE is 0.001 < cost_complexity < 0.009 with the best cost-complexity value at around 0.004.

Random Forest Autoplot

autoplot(rf_tune, metric = "rmse")

In the random forest model, we tuned the the number of randomly selected predictor variables considered at each split (mtry), the number of trees in the random forest model (trees), and the minimal node size, namely, the minimum number of observations required to split a node (min_n). From the plot above we see that as mtry increases, the RMSE decreases meaning that the model is better. Hyperparameters trees and min_n do not seem to have a significant impact.

Best Model

As we observed, random forest performed the best out of our five models with hyperparameters: mtry = 6, trees = 485, and min_n = 13.

Fitting to Training Data

Let’s fit our best model to the training data.

best_rf <- select_best(rf_tune, metric = "rmse")
final_wf_rf <- finalize_workflow(rf_workflow, best_rf)
final_fit_rf <- fit(final_wf_rf, movie_train)

final_rf_test <- augment(final_fit_rf, new_data = movie_test)

Testing the Model

Now, we’ll test our best model on the testing data.

rmse(final_rf_test, truth = vote_average, estimate = .pred)

The random forest model with mtry = 6, trees = 485, and min_n = 13 produced a testing RMSE of ~0.63 which is lower than the estimated testing RMSE we obtained from cross-validation (which was ~0.66). So, our testing RMSE of 0.63 means that the model’s predictions, on average, deviate by about 0.63 units from the true ratings, which is decent considering that our ratings are on a 0-10 scale!

Take a look at the plot of the predicted values versus the actual values:

final_rf_test %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = vote_average, y = .pred)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.5) +
  #xlim(0,10) +
  #ylim(0,10) +
  geom_abline(col = "red")

Ideally, we want the dots to form a straight line, indicating that all of our observations were predicted accurately. Although our observations are not directly on the red line, they are centered around it and follow the same, upwards pattern.

Variable Importance

Since we specified importance = "impurity" in our random forest workflow, we can create and view a variable importance plot, namely, which variables were most important in predicting our outcome variable vote_average.

final_fit_rf %>% extract_fit_parsnip() %>%
  vip()

From our plot we see that vote_count was the most important in predicting vote_average. This make sense because more exposure, or a higher number of viewers, provides a more representative sample of the audience’s opinions. Interestingly, runtime was the second most important. This indicates that the duration of the movie was the second most impactful variable in predicting the average vote of a movie.

Conclusion

We have explored a lot of variables that could potentially affect the average vote of a movie and created models to predict this rating. In our EDA, we conducted a visual analysis of our outcome variable vote_average and its predictor variables: budget, popularity, revenue, runtime, vote_count, genre, production_company, and release_year. We observed that the mean of average votes in our dataset was around 6.3 on a 0-10 scale. Another interesting observation we found was that vote_count and revenue had a strong, positive correlation as well as revenue and budget.

We created and analyzed five models: (1) linear regression, (2) k-nearest neighbors, (3) elastic net, (4) pruned decision trees, and (5) random forest. Random forest performed the best with hyperparameters mtry = 6, trees = 485, and min_n = 13 and predicted the average movie rating fairly well based on the RMSE. This is not very surprising because random forest models are less prone to overfitting compared to other models, can handle non-linearity, and are overall more flexible.

The model that performed the worst was elastic net. Elastic net models, being a combination of lasso and ridge regression, introduce additional complexities compared to other models like linear regression or random forests which can lead to overfitting. Elastic net also penalizes the coefficients of correlated features, which can be problematic if the dataset contains multicollinearity, which in this case it does because we identified two highly correlated sets of variables in our correlation plot.

One lingering question I have is: what would have happened if we imputed all the missing data rather than omitting it? Would it have improved our model because we would’ve had more observations or was there just too much to impute that it would not be feasible? The proportion of missing data to the total size of the dataset seemed too large to impute, which is why I just omitted it, but losing so much data that could have been valuable leads me to wonder if there was a better way to handle this.

If I were to continue this project I would add more predictor variables. We only used one dataset from the larger dataset itself. If we were to merge this dataset with the ratings dataset, which contains individual user ratings for a large handful of movies, we could expand this project into a more personalized recommendation system. There is another dataset called credits.csv with cast and crew information. Merging this with our current dataset could potentially contain valuable information that improves our prediction and could have a significant effect on average movie rating. Perhaps A-list actors or illustrious directors could positively influence the average rating of a movie.

In conclusion, this project has been a fulfilling experience, merging my interest in movies with the practical application of machine learning. Exploring real-world datasets and implementing various models has equipped me with valuable skills for future data-driven projects and has greatly contributed to my growth as a data scientist. I am proud to have developed a model that predicts the average rating of a movie fairly well!
